        "Combat\n\nA typical combat encounter is a clash between two sides, involving weapon swings, feints, parries, footwork, and spellcasting. The game organizes combat into rounds and turns, with each round representing about 6 seconds in the game world. Each participant in the battle takes a turn during a round. The order of turns is determined at the beginning of a combat encounter when all participants, including player characters (PCs) and monsters, roll initiative. Once everyone has taken a turn, the fight continues to the next round unless one side has defeated the other.\n\nSurprise\n\nSurprise can occur when one side gains the advantage over the other by stealthily approaching or catching them off guard. The Game Master (GM) determines who might be surprised. If neither side is being stealthy, they automatically notice each other. To determine surprise, the GM compares the DEX (Stealth) checks of anyone hiding with the Perception score of each creature on the opposing side. Anyone who doesn't notice a threat is surprised at the start of the encounter. Being surprised means you can't move or take an action on your first turn of combat and can't take a reaction until your turn ends. It's possible for some members of a group to be surprised while others are not.\n\nInitiative\n\nInitiative determines the order of turns during combat. At the start of combat, everyone involved rolls initiative to determine the order of combatants' turns. The GM makes one roll for an entire group of identical creatures, so each member of the group acts at the same time. The combatants are ranked in initiative order from highest to lowest DEX check result. Initiative order remains the same from round to round. If there is a tie, the GM and players decide the order among tied characters and creatures. Optionally, tied characters and monsters can each roll a d20 to determine the order.\n\nYour Turn\n\nOn your turn, you can move a distance up to your speed and take one action. You decide whether to move or take your action first. Your speed is noted on your character sheet and represents how far you can move. The most common actions you can take are described in the Actions in Combat section of the game rules. Many class features and other abilities provide additional options for your action. You don't have to move or take an action if you can't decide what to do on your turn. In that case, consider taking the Dodge or Ready action, as described in the Actions in Combat section.\n\nBonus Actions\n\nVarious class features, spells, and other abilities allow you to take an additional action on your turn called a bonus action. For example, the Cunning Action feature allows a rogue to take a bonus action. You can take a bonus action only when a class feature, spell, or other special ability states that you can do something as a bonus action. You can take only one bonus action on your turn, so you must choose which one to use if you have more than one available. You choose when to take a bonus action during your turn, unless the timing of the bonus action is specified. If something prevents you from taking an action, it also prevents you from taking a bonus action.\n\nReactions\n\nCertain special abilities, spells, and situations allow you to take a reaction. A reaction is an instant response to a trigger, which can occur on your turn or someone else's. The most common type of reaction is the opportunity attack, which allows you to make an attack when a hostile creature moves out of your reach. When you take a reaction, you can't take another one until the start of your next turn. If your reaction interrupts another creature's turn, that creature can continue its turn right after the reaction.\n\nOther Activity on Your Turn\n\nYour turn can include minor actions or interactions that don't require your action or movement. You can communicate through brief talking and gestures at any time. You can interact with one object or feature of the environment for free during either your movement or action. For example, you could open a door during your move or draw your weapon as part of your Attack action. If you want to interact with a second object, you need to use your action. Some magical items and special objects require an action to use, as stated in their descriptions. The GM may require you to use an action for activities that require special care or present unusual obstacles, such as opening a stuck door or turning a crank to lower a drawbridge.\n\nMovement and Position\n\nIn combat, characters and monsters are in constant motion, often using movement and position to gain an advantage. On your turn, you can move a distance up to your speed. You can use as much or as little of your speed as you like, following the rules provided in the game. Your movement can include jumping, climbing, and swimming, either combined with walking or as your entire move. However you move, deduct the distance of each part of your move from your speed until it is used up or until you are done moving.\n\nBreaking Up Your Move\n\nYou can break up your movement on your turn by using some speed before and the remainder after your action. For example, if you have a speed of 30 feet, you can move 10 feet, take your action, and then move 20 feet.\n\nUsing Different Speeds\n\nIf you have more than one speed, such as a walking speed and a flying speed, you can switch back and forth between them during your move. Each time you switch, subtract the distance you have already moved from the new speed. The result determines how much farther you can move. If the result is 0 or less, you can't use the new speed during the current move. For example, if you have a speed of 30 feet and a flying speed of 60 feet, you could fly 20 feet, then walk 10 feet. If you wanted to walk any farther, you would be done for your move, but you could still use your flying speed to move 30 feet more.\n\nDifficult Terrain\n\nCombat rarely takes place in open areas. The game recognizes various challenging terrains, such as rubble, undergrowth, steep stairs, snow, and shallow bogs, that can impede movement. Each foot of movement in difficult terrain costs an extra foot. Difficult terrain can also include the space of another creature, which counts as difficult terrain for you.\n\nBeing Prone\n\nCombatants can find themselves lying on the ground either because they are knocked down or choose to throw themselves down. When prone, a creature has the prone condition. Dropping prone is free and doesn't require any movement, but standing up from prone costs movement equal to half your speed. Crawling is the most efficient way to move while prone, with each foot of movement while crawling costing an extra foot. Crawling through difficult terrain costs 3 feet of movement per foot crawled.\n\nMoving Around Other Creatures\n\nYou can move through a nonhostile creature's space, but moving through a hostile creature's space is only possible if the creature is two or more sizes larger or smaller than you. Another creature's space counts as difficult terrain for you, and you can't willingly end your move in its space. If you leave a hostile creature's reach during your move, you provoke an opportunity attack from that creature.\n\nFlying Movement\n\nFlying creatures can enjoy many benefits, but they must also deal with the danger of falling. If a flying creature is knocked prone, has its speed reduced to 0, or is otherwise deprived of the ability to move, the creature falls unless it has the ability to hover or is being held aloft by magic, such as the fly spell.\n\nCreature Size\n\nEach creature takes up a specific amount of space on the battlefield. Size categories determine the space a creature controls in combat. The size categories are Tiny, Small, Medium, Large, Huge, and Gargantuan. A creature's space is not an expression of its physical dimensions but rather the area it effectively controls.\n\nSpace\n\nA creature's space is the area, usually expressed in feet, that it controls in combat. It reflects both its physical dimensions and the area it needs to fight effectively. For example, a Medium creature controls a 5-foot square.\n\nSqueezing into a Smaller Space\n\nA creature can squeeze through a space that is large enough for a creature one size smaller than it. For example, a Large creature can squeeze through a passage that is only 5 feet wide. While squeezing, a creature must spend extra movement for each foot it moves there, and it has disadvantage on attack rolls and DEX saves. Attacks against the creature have advantage while it's squeezing.\n\nActions in Combat\n\nThe most common action in combat is the Attack action, which allows you to make a melee or ranged attack. Depending on your class, you may also have access to additional actions. Spells and special abilities can provide other action options. When you describe an action not detailed elsewhere in the rules, the GM determines whether it is possible and may require rolls to determine success or failure.\n\nAttack\n\nThe Attack action allows you to make one melee or ranged attack against a target within your attack's range. Different weapons and spells have specific rules for making an attack. When making an attack, roll a d20 and add the appropriate modifiers. If the total meets or exceeds the target's AC, the attack hits. Certain features, such as the fighter's Multiattack, allow you to make multiple attacks with this action.\n\nCast a Spell\n\nSpellcasting characters and some monsters can take the Cast a Spell action in combat to cast a spell. You can only cast spells with a casting time of 1 action using this action. Spells with longer casting times require their own specific actions.\n\nDash\n\nThe Dash action grants you additional movement on your turn. You can move up to your speed, multiplied by two, when you take this action. For example, if your speed is 30 feet, you can move up to 60 feet with a Dash action.\n\nDisengage\n\nThe Disengage action allows you to move without provoking opportunity attacks for the rest of your turn. This can be useful if you need to move away from an enemy without risking being attacked.\n\nDodge\n\nThe Dodge action allows you to focus on avoiding attacks until the start of your next turn. While dodging, you have advantage on Dexterity saving throws, and attack rolls against you have disadvantage if you can see the attacker. This benefits is lost if you become incapacitated or if your speed drops to 0.\n\nHelp\n\nThe Help action allows you to aid another creature in completing a task. This can involve providing advantage on ability checks or helping an ally to make their attack more effective. The specifics of how this action works depend on the situation and the GM's rulings.\n\nHide\n\nThe Hide action allows you to make a Dexterity (Stealth) check to hide, attempting to avoid detection. If you succeed, you gain certain benefits described in the rules for unseen attackers and targets.\n\nReady\n\nThe Ready action allows you to prepare an action or move to be triggered by a specific circumstance on someone else's turn. For example, you could ready an attack to be made when a creature steps on a trap. This action requires you to use your reaction, and you must state the trigger and the action or move you will take when the trigger occurs.\n\nSearch\n\nThe Search action allows you to devote your attention to finding something. The GM may require ability checks, such as Wisdom (Perception) or Intelligence (Investigation), depending on the nature of your search.\n\nUse an Object\n\nThe Use an Object action allows you to interact with an object or feature in the environment. This action is usually required when interacting with more than one object on your turn or when interacting with a complex or tricky object that requires an ability check.\n\nMaking an Attack\n\nWhen making an attack, the attacker rolls an attack roll to determine if the attack hits the target. The attack roll is determined by rolling a d20 and adding relevant modifiers. If the attack roll equals or exceeds the target's AC, the attack hits. The specific modifiers and rules for the attack depend on the weapon or spell being used.\n\nAttack Rolls\n\nAn attack roll is determined by rolling a d20 and adding the relevant modifiers. The two most common modifiers are the ability modifier, which is either Strength or Dexterity depending on the weapon being used, and the proficiency bonus, which is added if the attacker is proficient with the weapon. The attack roll is compared to the target's AC to determine if the attack hits.\n\nModifiers to the Roll\n\nWhen making an attack roll, the attacker adds their ability modifier and proficiency bonus, if applicable, to the roll. The ability modifier used depends on the weapon being used. When using a spell that requires an attack roll, the ability modifier used is based on the spellcasting ability of the spellcaster.\n\nRolling 1 or 20\n\nIf the attack roll is a 20, it is a critical hit and the attack automatically hits, regardless of any modifiers or the target's AC. The attacker then rolls all of the attack's damage dice twice and adds them together. If the attack roll is a 1, it is a critical failure and the attack automatically misses, regardless of any modifiers or the target's AC.\n\nUnseen Attackers and Targets\n\nWhen attacking a target that you can't see, either because they are hiding or due to visibility conditions, you have disadvantage on the attack roll. This disadvantage applies even if you can guess the target's location or if you can hear, but not see, the target. If the target isn't in the location you targeted, the attack automatically misses. On the other hand, if you are unseen by a target, you have advantage on attack rolls against them. If you are both unseen and unheard when making an attack, you give away your location when the attack hits or misses.\n\nCover\n\nCover can provide protection during combat, making it more difficult for attackers to hit their targets. There are three degrees of cover: half cover, three-quarters cover, and total cover. Half cover grants a +2 bonus to AC and Dexterity saves, while three-quarters cover grants a +5 bonus. Total cover means that the target can't be targeted directly by an attack or spell.\n\nRanged Attacks\n\nRanged attacks involve using weapons or spells to strike at targets from a distance. Each ranged attack has a specific range, and attacks beyond the weapon's normal range have disadvantage. Certain weapons, such as crossbows and nets, have different rules for ranged attacks. Attacks made with ranged weapons in close combat have disadvantage unless the weapon is a dagger, javelin, shortsword, spear, or trident.\n\nMelee Attacks\n\nMelee attacks involve making physical strikes at targets within your reach. Different weapons and spells have specific rules for making melee attacks. Most creatures have a reach of 5 feet, allowing them to make melee attacks against targets within 5 feet of them. Some creatures, typically larger ones, have longer reach for melee attacks. Unarmed strikes, such as punches or kicks, also count as melee attacks. Attacks made with melee weapons add the relevant ability modifier to the damage.\n\nOpportunity Attacks\n\nAn opportunity attack is a reaction that can be triggered when a hostile creature moves out of your reach. When this happens, you can make a melee attack against the provoking creature. The opportunity attack occurs right before the creature leaves your reach. Taking the Disengage action can avoid provoking an opportunity attack.\n\nTwo-Weapon Fighting\n\nWhen you have a light melee weapon in each hand, you can use the Two-Weapon Fighting action to make a second attack with the weapon in your other hand as a bonus action. This action allows you to make an additional attack but does not add your ability modifier to the damage unless the modifier is negative. The weapon used for the bonus attack can be thrown if it has the thrown property.\n\nGrappling\n\nThe Grapple action allows you to make a special melee attack to grapple a creature. You can use one free hand to try and seize the target. This is a contested check, with the attacker making a Strength (Athletics) check and the target choosing between a Strength (Athletics) or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. If the attacker wins, the target becomes grappled. The grappled condition specifies how it can end.\n\nShoving\n\nThe Shove action allows you to make a special melee attack to shove a creature. This can knock the target prone or push it away from you. Like grappling, shoving is a contested check, with the attacker making a Strength (Athletics) check against the target's Strength (Athletics) or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. Success allows the attacker to knock the target prone or push it 5 feet away."
