        "Talents represent the specific ways an adventurer has improved over the course of their adventures. Talents are divided into three categories: magic talents, martial talents, and technical talents. Your class typically determines which talent lists you have access to. Talents are gained in two main ways:\n\n1. When a character chooses their background during character creation, they select one talent from a list of options provided in the background.\n\n2. When a character class grants an Improvement, they choose a talent from the list specified by their class features, assuming the character meets any necessary prerequisites.\n\nMAGIC TALENTS:\n\nMost magic talents affect a character's spellcasting abilities, but they also include features that strengthen the mind and defend against harmful magic effects.\n\n1. COMBAT CASTING:\n   - Prerequisite: Ability to Cast Spells\n   - Benefits:\n     - Automatically succeed on concentration saves for spells with a DC equal to or lower than 8 + your PB.\n     - Use your reaction to cast a cantrip instead of making a melee attack when a hostile creature provokes an opportunity attack from you.\n     - Use a shield or weapon as a spellcasting focus and perform somatic spell components with the same hand or hands holding the focus.\n\n2. ELEMENTAL SAVANT:\n   - Prerequisite: Ability to Cast at Least One Spell that Deals Damage\n   - Benefits:\n     - Choose one elemental damage type: acid, cold, fire, lightning, or thunder. Convert the damage type of a spell to your chosen element.\n     - Reroll any damage dice results of 1 for a spell that naturally uses your chosen elemental damage type.\n     - Can be selected multiple times to choose different damage types.\n\n3. MENTAL FORTITUDE:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Once per long rest, when you fail an INT, WIS, or CHA save, you can reroll the save.\n     - Repeat the save at the end of each turn to end charmed, frightened, or stunned conditions caused by a failed save.\n\n4. MENTAL PROWESS:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Increase CHA, INT, or WIS ability score by 1 (up to a maximum of 20).\n     - Can be selected multiple times.\n\n5. RITUALIST:\n   - Prerequisite: Ability to Cast Spells\n   - Benefits:\n     - Gain a ritual book and cast ritual spells from it.\n     - Choose a circle of magic: arcane or divine, and select rituals from that circle's list.\n     - Add one ritual spell of each spell ring you have unlocked to your ritual book.\n     - Add one new ritual spell of a ring you gain access to with each new level.\n     - Must be from the same circle of magic and a ring you have spell slots for.\n     - Can be selected multiple times.\n\n6. SCHOOL SPECIALIZATION:\n   - Prerequisite: Ability to Cast Spells\n   - Benefits:\n     - Choose one of the eight schools of magic.\n     - +1 to attack rolls and increased DC for spells from the chosen school.\n     - Halved gold and time to copy spells of that school into a spellbook.\n     - Can be selected multiple times.\n\nMARTIAL TALENTS:\n\nMartial talents affect a character's combat abilities, including enhancements to overall fitness and the ability to wield weaponry.\n\n1. ARMORED COMBATANT:\n   - Benefits:\n     - +1 AC while wearing medium or heavy armor.\n     - Reduce bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage taken by an amount equal to your PB.\n\n2. ARTILLERIST:\n   - Prerequisite: STR Score of 13 or Higher\n   - Benefits:\n     - Ignore loading property of simple and martial weapons.\n     - Advantage on attack rolls with siege weapons or large projectile-launching objects.\n\n3. COMBAT CONDITIONING:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Increase hit point maximum based on previous levels and each new level.\n     - Ignore hit dice rolls lower than your PB when recovering hit points.\n\n4. HAND TO HAND:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Unarmed strikes deal 1d4 + STR bludgeoning damage.\n     - Advantage on ability checks to initiate or escape a grapple.\n\n5. PHYSICAL FORTITUDE:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Once per long rest, reroll a failed STR or CON save.\n     - Repeat saves at the end of each turn to end blinded, deafened, paralyzed, or poisoned conditions caused by a failed save.\n\n6. PHYSICAL PROWESS:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Increase STR, DEX, or CON ability score by 1 (up to a maximum of 20).\n     - Can be selected multiple times.\n\n7. RANGED WEAPON MASTERY:\n   - Benefits:\n     - No disadvantage on ranged weapon attack rolls at long range.\n     - No disadvantage when a hostile creature is within 5 feet.\n     - Ignore half and three-quarters cover.\n\n8. TWO WEAPON MASTERY:\n   - Benefits:\n     - +1 AC while wielding a different melee weapon in each hand.\n     - Use the bonus action attack granted by two-weapon fighting even with non-light weapons.\n     - Draw or stow two one-handed weapons simultaneously.\n\nTECHNICAL TALENTS:\n\nTechnical talents affect a character's noncombat abilities, granting utility-based improvements to social encounters, exploration, and object interactions.\n\n1. AWARE:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Treat any d20 roll of 9 or lower on initiative as a 10.\n     - Cannot be affected by the surprised condition.\n     - Hidden targets don't have advantage on attack rolls against you.\n\n2. DUNGEONEER:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Advantage on ability checks to actively search for secret doors or traps.\n     - No penalty to passive Perception when traveling at a fast pace.\n     - Advantage on saves to avoid or resist traps and hazards.\n\n3. FIELD MEDIC:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Stabilize a dying creature with first aid, restoring 1 HP.\n     - As an action, tend to a creature, restoring hit points equal to twice their CON modifier. Can only be used once per short or long rest.\n\n4. POLYGLOT:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Learn three languages of your choice.\n     - Advantage on a single CHA ability check when conversing in a known language with another creature.\n     - Add PB to rolls related to understanding unknown verbal or written languages, doubling PB if proficient in a relevant skill or tool.\n\n5. TRADE SKILLS:\n   - Choose a profession and gain the following benefits:\n     - Proficiency with one skill and one type of tool or vehicle relevant to the chosen profession.\n     - Advantage on ability checks where the use of a tool and skill would both apply if proficient in both.\n     - Can be selected multiple times with different professions.\n\n6. TOUCH OF LUCK:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Gain 2 Luck points instead of 1 when failing an attack roll or save.\n     - Reset Luck points to d4 + 1 if reaching 6 points.\n\n7. WELL-ROUNDED:\n   - Benefits:\n     - Increase any ability score of your choice by 1 (up to a maximum of 20).\n     - Can be selected multiple times with different ability scores.\n\nLUCK:\n\nLuck is a special resource that can be used to influence the result of checks.\n\n- Start with 0 Luck points.\n- Gain Luck points when failing an attack roll, save, or as rewards from the GM.\n- Can have a maximum of 5 Luck points.\n- Reset Luck points to a d4 + 1 if reaching 6 points.\n- Spend Luck points to add to any d20 roll or to reroll a d20.\n- Luck cannot offset natural 1 or create a natural 20."
